Northeastern University is a national research university that is student centered,
practice oriented and urban. With rising SAT scores, an increasing number of
applicants, a dramatic increase in student retention, promising growth in externally
sponsored research, a strong commitment to the City of Boston and a cooperative
education program that distinguishes Northeastern from other institutions of higher
education, the University is poised to achieve its wide range of goals and objectives.

The 2000 Institutional Master Plan and its subsequent Amendments identified
Northeastern’s long-term needs, goals, and objectives as being those corresponding
to the development projects proposed in the Institutional Master Plan such as
additional student housing, enhanced technology, replacement of outdated
buildings, and long term preventative maintenance.
The quality of Northeastern’s academic programs is the driving force in the evolution
of the University. Attracting talented faculty and student is key to improving the
educational and research excellence of the University. Increasingly, student housing
is an important factor in attracting students. Housing students on campus is also
critically important to the University’s neighbors. Cooperation with its neighbors is
important to the University and necessary to its future success. The focus of this IMP
Amendment primarily is driven by the need to provide additional student housing.

Northeastern is located in the Fenway, Mission Hill and Roxbury area of Boston and
has many different types of neighbors. The neighborhoods surrounding the
University are not independent from the University as many students and faculty of
Northeastern contribute greatly to the nearby communities. With these diverse
neighbors also comes a wide array of land uses. The land uses around the
Northeastern campus vary and consist of institutional, high and medium-density
Northeastern resides in the City of Boston and is subject to city plans and policies.
Current plans and policies that affect the University’s planning framework include
the ongoing Urban Ring project, the recently completed Roxbury Master Plan and the
ongoing Community Task Force planning process. Both planning projects promote
the need for transit-oriented development at transit nodes. The University relies on
public transportation for its students and faculty, and thus new development will
continue to focus on the benefits of public transportation to serve the future needs of
the University. For example, the proposed Parcel 18 West development is a high-
density mixed-used student residence development at the Ruggles MBTA Station
thus reducing vehicle trips substantially, which is one of many goals of transit-
The major planning process that the University is committed to enhancing and
continuing is the Community Task Force process described in the following section.
In an effort to engage in a more collaborative and open process regarding the
University’s planning for physical development, the University, the City of Boston,
the Boston Redevelopment Authority, the University’s neighbors from the Fenway,
Roxbury and Mission Hill, as well as local elected officials, joined together to attempt
a new form of university/community discussion. This new form of collaboration was
founded on the notion that more could be gained by all parties involved if the
community was consulted during the University’s planning process versus the
former procedure of engaging the community at the end of the University’s planning
Accordingly, a new Community Task Force was established to work proactively with
the University in the development of the next phase of its Master Plan. Northeastern
University has participated in this open process since December 2004. This public
participation process is the first of its kind and had never been attempted in the City
of Boston. In this open process a wide range of diverse interests such as community
activists, community leaders, elected officials and any member of the general public
who wanted to attend, came together to assist Northeastern University to develop a
workable plan. Although this process took longer than originally anticipated, the
resulting plan is supported by all those involved.
The Community Task Force (the “Task Force”) is comprised of fourteen members
from the Mission Hill, Roxbury and Fenway neighborhoods and seven elected
officials serving as ex-officio members. Each Task Force member was nominated by a
local elected official, and appointed by the Mayor’s Office and Boston
Redevelopment Authority. The Task Force includes the following representatives
The University committed to a public process that departs from the approach of
having institutions inform neighbors of their short- and long-range plans. Rather, it
seeks to include neighbors during the process of developing those plans. This
involvement is not intended to replace the community processes that are part of the
Article 80 process. The University views the work of the Task Force as expanding
and extending the community review process by involving the community earlier
and more extensively in the process of developing the IMP.
The University has sought the input of the Task Force in the development of the
residential projects included in the proposed amendment to the IMP. As part of this
effort, the Community Task Force or sub-groups have met 22 times since December
2004 to discuss on-campus housing issues, as well as other development needs.
While meetings of the Task Force are geared toward participation by Task Force
members, the meetings are open to the public and questions and comments from the
audience as well as the Task Force members, have regularly been part of the
The primary need for the Third Amendment to Northeastern University’s 2000
Institutional Master Plan was brought about by a Memorandum of Agreement
(MOA) signed by the University and the City of Boston in July 2004. In addition to
other requirements, the MOA requires Northeastern to submit IMP amendments to
the Boston Redevelopment Authority (BRA) to “…include two or more on-campus
housing developments on Northeastern owned land containing a minimum of 1,250
The impetus for the MOA between the City and the University was two fold. The
first was the University leasing private housing for the purposes of housing students.
The second was the impact of a large number of students living in the surrounding
neighborhoods. In response to community concerns, the University agreed to a plan
for phasing out its inventory of leased off-campus beds under its Master Lease
Property Program (MLPP) by expanding on-campus housing and to implement a
number of measures for improving property management, and safety and security in
leased properties. The MOA provides for a five-year phase-out of the 750 beds in the
MLPP commencing with the issuance of construction permits for on-campus
housing. The review and approval of the Third Amendment to the 2000 IMP, and
related Draft Project Impact Reports, will allow the University to meet the terms of
the MOA. In accordance with the MOA, the University is proposing to phase out the
MLPP according to the following schedule:
To meet the requirements of the MOA, the University initially presented a proposal
to the Task Force to construct an 855-bed residence hall on the North Lot and a 705-
bed residence hall on the Camden Lot. Both sites were selected, in part, because they
are parking lots that could be relatively quickly developed. No structures would
need to be razed and no replacement spaces for razed structures would need to be
constructed before construction of the residence halls could commence. In addition,
the North Lot is adjacent to existing campus housing and dining facilities in Speare
and Stetson Halls. The Camden Lot is adjacent to a pedestrian crossing of the Orange
Line and Commuter Rail tracks and is relatively close to academic and student
housing buildings on campus. The University presented conceptual plans for the
Camden Lot and alternative site layouts for the North Lot.
Members of the Task Force expressed opposition to the development of the two sites
for housing because of concern over the potential impacts on local neighborhoods. In
response to these concerns, Northeastern embarked on an extensive effort to work
with the Task Force to assess the potential use of alternative campus sites for
University housing. This effort focused on providing the number of beds required by
the MOA, meeting the schedule set forth in the MOA, the cost of developing
alternative sites, and the number of beds that could be developed within the financial
capability of the University. As part of this effort, the University made the following
The University reviewed the addition of housing under the existing ten-year
Institutional Master Plan with the Task Force. Since 1999, the University has added
2,989 beds to its on-campus housing supply. As a result of these additions and the
leased units, the University’s housing capacity is 50 percent of its undergraduate
One of the critical things the University wanted Task Force members and the broader
community to understand was the fact that of the 7,314 occupied beds (2004), the
University would lose 1,023 undergraduate beds due to the phasing out the MLPP as
per the MOA, the implementation of an agreement to convert 10 Coventry Street to
graduate housing, and the expiration of a five-year variance which allowed the
University to increase some student residence rooms from double to triple
occupancy. This was critically important as it showed that by simply building the
MOA prescribed minimum 1,250 beds, the University and the community would
only net an additional 227 beds. By providing 1,800 additional beds as described in
this Amendment, plus the 229 beds in Residence Hall F, the University will increase
the total number of student beds in university-controlled units by 777 beds. The net
result of all these changes will be to increase on-campus housing to 8,320 beds. Based
on full-time undergraduate enrollment stabilizing at approximately 15,000, the
University housing capacity will increase to approximately 55 percent of full-time
To assist the Task Force and the University in evaluating the potential use of other
campus sites for University housing, Northeastern presented an extensive inventory
of existing University properties. This inventory included location (address), age,
year acquired by the University, gross square footage, number of floors, type of
construction, and existing uses. The inventory helped identify sites based on
minimizing disruption of existing campus activities and the cost of demolishing
existing structures and building replacement structures.
The Northeastern University Chief Financial Officer presented information on the
financial capacity of the University to build additional student housing. Since
University housing is entirely debt financed, this analysis focused on the University’s
borrowing capacity over the next five years. Because of extensive financing of
previous residence hall construction, the University’s borrowing capacity is limited
to about $300 million over the next five years. $100 million is needed to finance non-
housing capital needs leaving about $200 million for development of housing. These
estimates are subject to a variety of financial and external market conditions
To the extent that development of housing eliminates existing facilities and requires
construction of replacement facilities, the number of beds that can be built will be
reduced. This was demonstrated with the example of the 1,560 beds proposed on the
North and Camden Lots. Since those sites are vacant, the 1,560 beds could be
constructed for about $180 million. If dormitories were placed on sites requiring
razing and replacing existing structure, only about 900 beds or less depending on
housing style could be constructed because of the cost of replacing existing space.
Based on the inventory and suggestions of the Task Force, several sites were
identified for more detailed analysis of the feasibility of building University housing
closer to the center of the campus.
The University provided a more detailed analysis of several sites identified by the Task

each site for housing, an estimate of the number of beds that could be constructed on
each site, the cost of constructing those beds, the cost of demolishing existing buildings,
consideration of where replacement space would be located, and the cost of providing
The end result of the multi-meeting discussion was that placing all the new beds in
this area would create several tall buildings, some as high as 38 stories, which was
not an acceptable solution. The point was made that if existing buildings had to be
razed to create housing sites, it would take twice as long to create the housing
facilities and in order to stay within the current financial capacity, decrease the
number of beds that could be built.

Infrastructure improvements are inevitable in planning new campus projects. Each
individual development project will contain infrastructure and utility improvements
to accommodate that particular project. From a campus-wide perspective, the only
infrastructure improvement contemplated at this time addresses upgrading Boston
and Water Sewer Commission (BWSC) infrastructure. To eliminate surface water
run-off flowing to an existing combined sewer located on Gainsborough Street, the
University is in the process of installing a pump station which will divert stormwater
flow to an existing storm drain located on Gainsborough Street. In addition, the main
campus drainage system will be connected to the Old Stoney Brook culvert located
on Forsyth Street, providing an emergency overflow in the event of high surface
runoff or stormwater pump failure. The University will continue to work with the
BWSC to finalize plans for the upgrade to the stormwater infrastructure on campus.

In the mid-1980s Northeastern University was the largest private university in the
United States with a total enrollment in excess of 50,000 students. By 1990, given the
economics of higher education the university adopted a strategy known as “Smaller
and Better”, committing itself to a significantly reduced enrollment. Today the
Some addresses in the MLPP change yearly.
University’s enrollment plan calls for a full-time undergraduate day student
enrollment of approximately 15,000. This is based on a model that includes
approximately 2,800 new first-time, full-time freshman enrolled in each fall semester
incoming class. Over the past three years, the size of the incoming freshman class has
averaged 2,855 slightly above our incoming class target. Over a more extended
period of years, the highest incoming class level reached 3,457 and the lowest 2,778.
Refined enrollment management has enabled the university to better obtain its
targeted enrollment each year. Overall enrollment has averaged 14,636, well within
The admission of undergraduate students involves a prediction of the percentage of
students who will accept an offer of admission. Since the year 2000, the application
pool for the University has increased from 14,760 to 27,168. In order to limit
enrollment given the increased appeal of the university, the rate of admission has
decreased from 77 percent in 2000 to 45 percent in 2006. The University then expects
to receive a yield of 25 percent to 27 percent from this pool of admitted students who
will choose Northeastern as the one institution they will attend among a variety of
other offers. Many factors go into a student’s decision to choose one university
among the list of options, making this a challenging prediction. Each year the
University builds its enrollment model based on 2,800 freshmen and admits the class
expecting yield to meet the targeted enrollment. It also should be noted that the
University has benefited from significantly increased levels of student retention and
graduation rates that were realized sooner than was anticipated. As a result, the
improvements in retention have yielded an overall enrollment beyond that projected
The University’s plan, consistent with its original vision to be smaller and better,
calls for the institution to be selective in the enrollment of full-time undergraduate
students and maximize the quality of these students as evidenced by their academic
profiles. Accordingly, enrollments that exceed these targets stretch the allocation of
both financial and physical resources to levels that are not in the interest of the
university. This was experienced in the fall of 2000 as the University yielded an
incoming class in excess of its plan, causing intense strain on the University’s
The process of admitting students in the current market is by no means an exact
science. The annual population of 18 year olds coming out of high school has
increased nationally by more than 660,000 since 1994 and whereas in the past about
55 percent of these students would seek admission to colleges and universities, that
figure is now approximately 77 percent. This, coupled with the increased interest in
Northeastern University in the marketplace of higher education, has resulted in a
demand that is unprecedented in recent history. Northeastern’s focus is on the
quality of its students not in the increased size of the population. Thus, the plan for
the future remains as has been previously stated: a freshman class of approximately
2,800 students and overall full-time undergraduate enrollment of approximately

page.text: The IMP Overlay District is the feature of the Boston Zoning Code that allows
institutional uses to be governed by the provisions of an Institutional Master Plan
rather than by underlying zoning. However, only those parcels specifically requested
to be added to the Institutional Master Plan Overlay District will be voted on by the
Boston Zoning Commission as part of a zoning map amendment (see Table 3-2 and
Figure 3-1 for proposed properties to be incorporated in the IMP Overlay District).
With the exception of Parcel 18 West and the Gainsborough Garage, discussed
previously, the remaining properties are discussed below

text.b: Properties to be Added to the IMP Overlay District

page.text: The Gainsborough Parking Lot, located across the street from the Gainsborough
Garage site described above, is an approximately 9,500 SF site and is currently used
as parking. The site is located in the Fenway Neighborhood District in the
Institutional Subdistrict, which allows an FAR of 8.0 and a building height of 90 feet.
College and University uses are allowed as of right.
The St. Ann’s Church site, located at 77 St. Stephen Street, is an approximately 20,000
SF lot which was previously used as a Roman Catholic Church with approximately
21 parking spaces (see Figure 3-2 for floor plans). St. Ann’s Church is located in the
Fenway Neighborhood District, Multifamily Residential 1 District, a Neighborhood
Design Overlay District and a Restricted Roof Structure Overlay District. The
underlying zoning provides for a 4.0 FAR, a 60-foot height limit and a 20-foot rear
yard setback. The current building height is approximately four stories, or 50 feet and
there are 21 parking spaces on site. Within the MFR1 zoning district, residential uses,
community uses and certain cultural uses are allowed by right; educational uses are
conditional; and most business uses are prohibited. As university use requires proper
zoning, the University is proposing to include St. Ann’s Church in the IMP Overlay
The University does not intend to significantly alter the current uses of the property
in the next five years. The anticipated uses in the near future are as multi-purpose
meeting space for public assemblies, arts, cultural and community-based events,
chapel services, recreation, academic and parking. The University does not intend to
demolish the Church; however some structural repairs and upgrades will need to
occur. Because this property is not on the University’s immediate timeline for
renovation, there are no estimates of construction cost or schedule.
Once renovated, St. Ann's Church will be scheduled for use by students, faculty,
staff, neighbors and community groups in the same way, and by the same office as
other venues on campus including the Curry Student Center and Kerr Hall. St. Ann's
Church is an excellent location to continue the tradition of University facility use by
In addition, it is the intention of the University to use St. Ann's for church services
which will be primarily for its students but open to its neighbors. Finally, it is the
University’s hope that St. Ann's attracts student and community use that invites
positive collaborations and interactions between neighbors.
The Asian American Center, located at 109 Hemenway Street, sits on an
approximately 5,000 SF lot and was previously used as a multi-family residential
property (see Figure 3-3 for floor plans). The site is located in the Fenway
Neighborhood District, in a Neighborhood Institutional Subdistrict and a

FAR and a 60- foot height limit. Within the Neighborhood Institutional Subdistrict,
College and University use is allowed by right, but dormitory use requires a

Demand for on-campus housing far exceeds the capacity of the University’s existing
facilities. This demand has increased since the mid-1990’s due to the decreasing
supply of affordable off-campus housing and due to an increase in the proportion of
Northeastern’s students who come from outside the Boston area. Increasingly over
the recent years, community organizations and the Mayor’s Housing Task Force have
recommended that the City ask colleges and universities to build additional
dormitories in order to alleviate pressure on affordable housing in City
The University’s goal in the 2000 Master Plan was to provide quality university
housing for at least 6,500 undergraduate students by 2010. This goal was met in 2004,
and the University continues to increase its student housing options with Building F
coming on line this year. The University reviewed the addition of housing under the
existing ten-year Institutional Master Plan with the Task Force. Since 1999, the
University has added 2,989 beds to its on-campus housing supply. With the opening
of Building F on the West Campus, all on-campus housing included in the current
IMP is operational. As a result of these additions and the leased units, the
University’s operated housing capacity will be 50 percent of its undergraduate
As Northeastern increases its on-campus residential population, it must provide an
environment that encourages and reinforces interaction among students. Student life
facilities play an increasingly important role in attracting and retaining qualified
students. A quality student life experience includes a wide variety of recreation and
leisure spaces – both indoor and outdoor – and sufficient food and retail space.
Article 80D mandates that institutions submit a Student Housing Plan as part of the
IMP. The 2000 Master Plan did not include a substantial Student Housing Plan;
however, the University has been forthcoming with its student housing policy and
practices in subsequent amendments and during the Community Task Force public
One of the critical things the University wanted Task Force members and the broader
community to understand was the fact that of the 7,314 occupied beds (2004), the
University would lose 1,023 undergraduate beds due to the phasing out the MLPP as
per the MOA, the implementation of an agreement to convert 10 Coventry Street to
graduate housing, and the expiration of a five-year variance which allowed the
University to increase some student residence rooms from double to triple
occupancy. This was critically important as it showed that by simply building the
MOA prescribed minimum 1,250 beds, the University and the community would
only net an additional 227 beds. By providing 1,800 additional beds as described in
this Amendment, plus the 229 beds in Residence Hall F, the University will increase
the total number of student beds in university-controlled units by 777 beds. The net
result of all these changes will be to increase on-campus housing to 8,320 beds. Based
on full-time undergraduate enrollment stabilizing at approximately 15,000, the
University housing capacity will increase to approximately 55 percent of full-time
Northeastern owns or operates 38 residential properties in Boston for its student
population. For detailed information on these properties, including property
location, year built or purchased by Northeastern, building heights and gross square
footage and primary building use, see Table 2-1 in Chapter 2. Northeastern leases an
additional 25 properties in the area through the Master Lease Property Program,
accommodating a total of 716 students. A list of these properties is also provided in
The current policy is that housing is guaranteed to Freshman, Sophomores and
“Middlers.” There is no requirement that students accept this offer of housing at this
time. Further, there is no requirement that students live on campus.
Development and implementation of the freshman, sophomore, transfer,
upperclassmen, and graduate/law housing eligibility, room assignment and room
selection processes are managed by the Department of Residential Life whose offices
and central information desk are located in 4 Speare Commons, on Huntington
Avenue in Boston. Policies, procedures, processes, and timelines for students as they
relate to housing application and deposit are developed updated and communicated
to residents annually. Publications outlining processes and procedures are sent to
students and families each term. Residential Life implements a yearly housing lottery
The demand for on campus housing at Northeastern has exceeded capacity of the
existing facilities for years. Even with 2,989 new beds since 1999, the demand for
additional on-campus housing remains strong. This demand is demonstrated by the
long waiting list for student housing that has increased in the last few years. Each
year Northeastern keeps a waiting list for on-campus housing. This list is often in the
hundreds of students and at no time has every person on the wait list received on-
campus housing. Therefore, Northeastern anticipates all of its on-campus buildings
will remain fully occupied because of this significant demand by students.

text.b: Short and Long Term Housing Plans

page.text: As part of the Community Task Force (“CTF”) process, the University examined
short- and long-term housing goals specific to future housing sites. The CTF
recommends, and the University agreed, to several sites (Parcel 18 West, Cullinane
Hall and Gainsborough Garage) as appropriate sites for housing. The University is
proposing 1,800 beds on Parcel 18 West and the Cullinane Hall site, which will take
five years to develop. Future housing needs and development projects will be part of
the discussion for the University’s next IMP.
The Third Amendment of the IMP and the impending DPIRs for Residence Hall I on
Parcel 18 West and Residence Hall K at Cullinane Hall outline the short- and long-
term plans for housing the undergraduate student population at Northeastern. Once
the proposed construction is complete and through the update of the Institutional
Master Plan, the University will outline revised short- and long-term student
housing plans. Detail on the current short- and long-term housing plans are provided
The goal of increasing on-campus student housing has been addressed in recent
years and continues to be a focal point of the University’s future growth. As of fall
2006, the University had a total enrollment of approximately 25,000 students, as
This number differs from the Total Enrolled Students in Table 2-2 because of the
method of counting full- and part-time students prescribed by Federal reporting
standards. This is an accurate representation of the total Student Enrollment as of
While total enrollment has remained relatively stable in recent years, the demand for
on-campus, University-operated housing has exceeded the capacity of the
University’s existing facilities for on-campus housing for many years.
The University has opened eleven newly constructed or renovated student
residences since 1999, adding approximately 2,989 beds (see Table 4-2). As a result,
the percentage of undergraduate students housed on campus has increased from
one-third in 1998 to one-half of the total 7,543 occupied student beds in 2004. While
the University currently guarantees on-campus student housing for freshman and
sophomores, it is not mandated. Should the proposed projects be approved and
developed, Northeastern will require all freshmen and sophomores to live on

page.text: In response to continuing concerns raised by city leaders and community groups to
reduce the number of students living in neighborhoods adjacent to the campus, and
the additional concern raised regarding the University’s leasing of private housing, the
University and the City of Boston signed a Memorandum of Agreement (“MOA”) in
July, 2004. The MOA focuses on providing additional on-campus housing and phasing
out the University’s Master Lease Property Program (“MLPP”) through which the
University leases properties in the adjacent neighborhoods for student housing. The
MOA acknowledged base bed count of 750 beds in leased housing in 2004. The MOA
calls for phased reductions in leased housing by 10 percent in each of the first two
years, 20 percent in the third year, and 30 percent in the fourth and fifth years
following the receipt by the University of approvals for a minimum of 1,250 beds.
According to the MOA, the phasing-out of the MLPP will begin when the University
receives approvals for two or more additional on-campus residential projects
containing a minimum of 1,250 or more beds. The projects must be on land owned by
The Cullinane Hall (288 St. Botolph Street) and Parcel 18 West sites were identified as
the most appropriate locations to build additional on-campus housing by the Task
Force and the University. Providing housing on these sites will allow the University
to meet the terms of the MOA by providing approximately 1,800 beds in new on-
campus housing. This new housing will permit the phasing-out of 750 off-campus
University leased beds and replace approximately 250 beds which will be eliminated
when triples are converted to doubles and 10 Coventry Street is converted to

text.b: Student Housing Impact on Rental Market in Adjacent

page.text: Northeastern students and those from other area institutions have an impact on the
rental housing market, including Mission Hill, Fenway and in smaller part Roxbury.
In addition, students tend to pay higher rents than families. As a consequence, such
students displace permanent residents. Many students seek the least expensive
housing alternative. This may contribute to rental vacancies in the Fenway
neighborhood at the same time there are increases in the number of students from
this and other institutions living in the Mission Hill community. Without continued
development of new on campus housing, students will continue to seek the most
affordable housing options, preferably in neighborhoods closest to campus.
Consequently, as Northeastern and universities meet their commitments to increase
on-campus housing, we expect the demand for rental units in these communities to
ease. Eventually, if a significant number of students move on campus a larger supply
of housing may become available for residents. A possible side effect of a larger
supply of rental housing is lower asking prices and better maintenance, as landlords
will be forced to make their properties more attractive, financially attainable for
Within the next several weeks, the Draft Project Impact Reports (DPIR) for both
Residence Hall I on Parcel 18 West and Residence Hall K at Cullinane Hall will be
filed. These projects will construct approximately 1,800 new on-campus student beds
and will assist to mitigate the University’s impacts on the housing demand in the
surrounding neighborhoods. The University has added nearly 3,000 student on-
campus beds since 1999. Clearly, the University’s efforts have made, and will
continue to make, a positive impact on the local housing market.
The demand for on campus housing at Northeastern has exceeded capacity of the
existing facilities for years. Even with 2,989 new beds since 1999, the demand for
additional on-campus housing remains strong. This demand is demonstrated by the
long waiting list for student housing that has increased in the last few years. Each
year Northeastern keeps a waiting list for on-campus housing. This list is often in the
hundreds of students and at no time has every person on the wait list received on-
campus housing. Therefore, Northeastern anticipates all of its on-campus buildings
will remain fully occupied because of this significant demand by students.
Northeastern University takes the behavior of its students seriously. Expectations for
behavior are clearly spelled out in the Student Code of Conduct. “The Code of
Conduct applies to all registered undergraduate and graduate, full- and part-time
students as well as continuing education students enrolled at Northeastern
University. Student behavior occurring off campus that is in violation of the Code,
local, state or federal laws and could adversely affect the educational mission of the
University or it relationship with the surrounding community may subject students
to discipline pursuant to the Code of Conduct. ” Students sign an online
confirmation that they understand the Code of Conduct.
Violations of the Code of Conduct are handled through the Office of Student
Conduct and Conflict Resolution (OSCCR). Last academic year, there were
approximately 220 off-campus students who were disciplined for violations of the
code. Sanctions ranged from letters of censure to expulsion.
In an effort to further educate students of their responsibilities as members of the
University, and citizens of the City, Northeastern implements extensive outreach
programs. These include student and parent orientation sessions focused on the
institutions expectations around behavior, a mandatory freshman event with the
Boston Police and Northeastern Police Department, letters to students and parents on
appropriate behavior and the Code of Conduct, and Residential Life meetings with
The Office of Residential Life has oversight of those students who live in University
controlled housing (owned and leased). Oversight is managed in the form of full
time staff, resident directors, resident assistants, and community receptionists. All
residence halls are monitored with front door security. In addition, Northeastern
University Public Safety assigns officers to particular buildings as part of their
All students living in University controlled housing sign a Residence Hall/Dining
Hall License Agreement which makes clear that “All students must conduct
themselves in a manner consistent with the University's expectations, as stated in A
Guide to Residence Hall Living, the Student Handbook and the Residence Hall and
Dining License Agreement and any and all other applicable school policies,
The Office of Residential Life works with the Office of Student Conduct and Conflict
Resolution when violations of the Code of Conduct and/or the License Agreement
In regards to off-campus students, the University works closely with the Boston
Police Department in areas B-2 and D-4. This relationship includes paying for Boston
Police details focused on student behavior issues. In addition, the Office of
Government Relations and Community Affairs puts staff in the neighborhoods
Friday and Saturday night from mid-night to three o’clock am each weekend to
monitor and report on behavioral issues. The Community Affairs Office also works
closely with local elected officials, neighbors and other institutions in collectively
finding ways to curb inappropriate student behavior and increasing positive student
Supervision is a key way a university can help monitor and hold accountable its
students. For this reason, Northeastern has made aggressive changes to policies and
practices to improve supervision. Over the past several years, Northeastern has made
two fundamental changes. The first is, per the Memorandum of Agreement, the
University provides the same oversight in leased units as it does in residence halls.
By doing so, it has provided additional eyes and ears in the Fenway and Roxbury
community which has improved the quality of life for all residents.
The second is the University is a participant and supporter of the Boston Police
Department’s Operation Student Shield. In joining this effort, more institutional
resources are put towards off-campus student oversight. The result has been an
increase in the number of students held accountable for inappropriate behavior.
The thrust of the Urban Design Guidelines and Objectives as stated in the
Institutional Master Plan is to continue to develop the University as an urban campus
and as a result, to increase its connection to the city. This is achieved by opening the
campus to the surrounding neighborhoods both as a resource and as a portal, not a
The development of Parcel 18 West supports this objective in several ways:
h Focus on the site as a portal for the Roxbury Community to Ruggles Station
and downtown as well as the University and the Fenway Community;
h Provide uses compatible to the Roxbury Community including:
h Student residences that relieve pressure on the communities housing,
h Strengthened residential presence on Columbus Avenue, and
h Active uses along Tremont, Ruggles and Columbus providing valuable
retail services to the community and opportunities for Roxbury businesses;
h Expand the open space and pedestrian circulation network with a publicly
accessible courtyard and streetscape improvements on Columbus Avenue,
The development of both Residence Hall I on Parcel 18 West and Residence Hall K
on the Cullinane Hall site also address concerns about intrusion of the University
into the neighborhoods. The development of a significant number of residential
units relieves pressures on existing neighborhood housing resources and frees other
campus sites for academic expansion and upgrades.
In addition to these stated objectives, the IMP Amendment addresses community
concerns raised in subsequent public meetings.
